The '''Jadar''' ({{Lang-sr-cyr|Јадар}}, {{IPA-sh|jǎːdar|pron}}) region begins roughly at the [[Osečina]] and it is divided in two sub-regions: Upper Jadar (around Osečina), which is part of much larger region of [[Rađevina]], and Lower Jadar, which is also part of another, larger region of [[Podrinje]]. Center of the Lower Jadar is the town of [[Loznica]], which is not on the Jadar river, but some 10&nbsp;km to the southwest.

The region is located in the [[Jadar (Drina)|Jadar River valley]], bordered by the mountains of Vlašić, [[Cer (mountain)|Cer]], [[Gučevo]] and [[Sokolska planina]]. Lower Jadar is a low, agricultural area, while the Upper Jadar was an important mining region ([[antimony]] mines of Zavlaka and [[Bela Crkva (Krupanj)|Bela Crkva]]).

In August 1914, during [[World War I]], a major battle between the [[Austro-Hungary|Austro-Hungarian]] and Serbian army took place on the river. The Serbs defeated the Austrians. This battle known as [[Battle of Cer]], was the first victory of [[Allies of World War I|Allied forces]] in World War I. The march that is considered to be somewhat an alternative national anthem of Serbia depicts this battle (''[[Marš na Drinu]]'').

The mineral is notable for having a formula similar (lacking fluorine for a complete match) to that of the fictional [[kryptonite]], from the [[Superman]] [[comic book]]s and movies, was found in a mine in the Jadar region and has been named [[jadarite]], after the region.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stanley|first=Christopher J.|last2=Jones|first2=Gary C.|last3=Rumsey|first3=Michael S.|last4=Blake|first4=Christopher|last5=Roberts|first5=Andrew C.|last6=Stirling|first6=John A.R.|last7=Carpenter|first7=Graham J.C.|last8=Whitfield|first8=Pamela S.|last9=Grice|first9=Joel D.|date=2007-08-01|title=Jadarite, LiNaSiB3O7(OH), a new mineral species from the Jadar Basin, Serbia|url=http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/schweiz/ejm/2007/00000019/00000004/art00011;jsessionid=1rj3q58upvcbj.x-ic-live-02|journal=European Journal of Mineralogy|volume=19|issue=4|pages=575–580|doi=10.1127/0935-1221/2007/0019-1741}}</ref> <ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/6584229.stm 'Kryptonite' discovered in mine]</ref>

