[[File:Jamie Peck, geographer.jpg|thumbnail|Jamie Peck, Los Angeles, 2013]] '''Jamie Peck''' [[Royal Society of Canada|FRSC]] [[FAcSS]] (born July 9, 1962 in [[Kimberley, Nottinghamshire]], UK) is Canada Research Chair in Urban & Regional Political Economy and Professor of Geography at the [[University of British Columbia]], Canada.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=y_LRNVEAAAAJ&oi=ao |title=Jamie Peck - Google Scholar Citations |work=[[Google Scholar]] |accessdate=7 March 2013 }}</ref> He is the Managing Editor of ''[http://www.envplan.com/A.html Environment and Planning A]'' and the convenor of the [http://www.econgeog.net/ Summer Institute in Economic Geography].
==Background==
The recipient of [[Guggenheim Fellowship|Guggenheim]] and [[Harkness Fellowship|Harkness]] fellowships, he was previously Professor of Geography & Sociology at the [[University of Wisconsin-Madison]] and Professor of Geography at the [[University of Manchester]], and has held visiting positions at Johns Hopkins University, Oxford University, the National University of Singapore, University of the Witwatersrand, the University of Melbourne, the University of Nottingham, the University of Amsterdam, the University of Oslo, and Queen's University Belfast.
==Scholarly Contributions== Jamie Peck's research interests include the political economy of neoliberalization, [[Policy transfer|policy mobility]], economic governance, labor market theory and policy, and urban restructuring. His publications include ''[http://www.upress.umn.edu/book-division/books/fast-policy Fast policy: experimental statecraft at the thresholds of neoliberalism]'' (2015, with Nik Theodore), ''[http://global.oup.com/academic/product/constructions-of-neoliberal-reason-9780199580576;jsessionid=4BCF61BEF2A419F491A1E5942FF5C51F?cc=us&lang=en& Constructions of neoliberal reason]'' (2010), ''Contesting neoliberalism: urban frontiers'' (2007, coedited with Helga Leitner & [[Eric Sheppard]]), ''Politics and practice in economic geography'' (2007, coedited with Adam Tickell, Eric Sheppard & [[Trevor J. Barnes|Trevor Barnes]]), ''Workfare states'' (2001), ''Work-place: the social regulation of labor markets'' (1996), and the ''[http://ca.wiley.com/WileyCDA/WileyTitle/productCd-1444336800.html Wiley-Blackwell companion to economic geography]'' (2012, coedited with Trevor Barnes & Eric Sheppard). His current research is concerned with the sociology of global outsourcing, the politics of labor in the American South, and the political economy of urban restructuring.
==Recognition== * [[Ellen Churchill Semple]] award, [[Department of Geography, University of Kentucky]], 2008<ref>[http://geography.as.uky.edu/semple-day Ellen Churchill Semple Day] (accessed 30 June 2015)</ref> * Fellow of the Royal Society of Canada * Fellow of the Academy of the Social Sciences * Fellow, John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation (2006-2007) * Back Award, Royal Geographical Society, for "contributions to new economic geography" * Harkness Fellow, Commonwealth Fund of New York (1995-1996)
